    The procedure for changing from one system to another is called a system transition. It's common for someone to make changes to their family's or own personal system without giving it much thought. However, a system switch may be more difficult and problematic the larger the environment. A business or organization probably manages and maintains the financial and personal information of individuals, as well as information related to their livelihood, health, and well-being, or the infrastructure of a certain area. 
If something goes wrong or service is momentarily interrupted during a system switch at a hospital, power plant, or communication provider, it could have serious consequences. For these reasons, there are numerous methods for facilitating system transition.
A firm or organization may occasionally rely entirely on a system or procedure that is being changed. A new system is frequently incorporated into an already established larger system or series of systems and may just replace a portion of an organization's or company's operations; for example, switching to Canvas while continuing to use Clever, Skyward, etc. Changing systems will typically result in higher immediate costs, which may include labor hours, training costs, as well as possible monetary expenditures. When a new system is deployed, there may also be resistance from staff or customers. Prior to implementation, planning should be done in an effort to lessen any negative repercussions of the transition.""")
  elif(userchoice == "10"):
    print("""\033[1m IMPLEMENTATION METHODS \033[0m
    Different implementation strategies involve different trade-offs and hazards, and the "optimal strategy" is always depending on the circumstances. The following are the implementation strategies:
    PARALLEL: In this manner of implementation, both systems operate briefly in parallel. Prior to turning off the older system, this method also enables output of the new system to be measured. The business can continue to rely on the old system if the new system's functionality is unsatisfactory while working to resolve any problems. Due to the fact that both systems are being used simultaneously, this strategy can be costly and stressful. To maintain both functioning concurrently, this might call for additional computer or network resources, extra labor hours, and money outlays. If the two systems are quite dissimilar, the transition may be exceedingly inefficient for some time.
    BIG BANG/DIRECT/IMMEDIATE: This technique of implementation involves completely shutting down one system and bringing the other online as soon as preparations are finished. The least resource-intensive approach, but it necessitates frontloading training before the switchover. A third system or external location may also be required to transfer any data that has to be transferred from one system to the other while the switchover is taking place.
    PILOT: The pilot group or pilot site is the smaller portion of an organization or business that adopts the new system under this implementation strategy. In larger organizations and businesses with numerous divisions or locations, this is extremely typical. With this approach, the new system may be tested and problems worked out with less risk before being introduced to the entire organization. Changeover procedures for the rest of the organization can be planned once the new system has proven successful for the pilot group. When the new system is implemented, the pilot group can be used as a guide.
    PHASED: With this approach of implementation, the business or organization converts one module or section of the system at a time over time. This would imply that for data or processes to go back and forth between the new and old systems, they need to be sufficiently similar. Given that each component of the new system is implemented separately, training time is increased and the process will generally take longer. These implementation phases may be based on specific organizational processes or functions, or they may be based on specific organizational departments or teams.""")
