    The systems will probably change as two or more company entities integrate with one another, whether the merger is formal or more of an acquisition. 
By exerting more control over the process, lessening competition, or employing other strategies, merging or acquiring may aim to cut expenses. In the end, the merger should give the new organization or company a competitive edge.
One of the following integration strategies will be chosen as a consequence of system merging:
both systems may be preserved and developed to have the same functionality. Parallel operation of both systems incurs considerable maintenance expenses. 
A new system might take the place of both existing ones. This could lead to a new system that, generally, better suits the demands of the new company or organization, but it will come at a greater initial cost, including new training for all personnel. 
Pick the top system elements from each, then combine them. This gives the original employees of both companies some familiarity, but it may take them longer to get used to the entire system because some components operate according to habit rather than a complete change.
Choose the superior system and completely discard the inferior one. People who are accustomed to the abandoned system may oppose change, and there may be administrative problems. Those who are already familiar with the chosen system, however, might be resources because they have firsthand knowledge of it.""")
